I would like to thank Volker Hergert (VH) for contributing significantly to this issue.

I am close to finalizing my Isenegger project, which I started in the 1980s. In this issue you find a few new studies, new in the sense that they are not in Harolds HHdbVI database. I found these studies in my personal communications material which I obtained long ago from Paul Mueller-Breil (editor of Schweizerische Schachzeitung) and Joseph Maag (editor of the daily Bernise newspaper Der Bund).

New publications

Seven Chess Notes (June 2025)

GBR: =0004.12b7c1 FEN: 1N6/1K6/5p2/6p1/8/8/P3n3/2k5 w - - 0 1

1. a4 (1. Nd7? or 1.Nc6? 1 g4 -+ the g-pawn cant be stopped and it would be too late to let the a-pawn run. ) 1 Nd4 (1 g4 2. a5 g3 3. a6 g2 4. a7 g1=Q 5. a8=Q!1 would be a trivial draw. Black can instead use a knight fork to try and achieve more. ) 2. a5 (2. Nc6? Nxc6 3. Kxc6 g4 4. a5 g3 5. a6 g2 6. a7 g1=Q 7. a8=Q Qg2+ 8. Kd6 Qxa8 -+) 2 Nb3 3. a6 Nc5+ 4. Kc6 Otherwise, 4Nxa6 simply wins. 4 Nxa6 5. Nd7! Now its Whites turn to play around with knight forks. (5. Nxa6? g4 6. Nc5 g3 7. Nd3+ Kd2 8. Nf4 Ke3 -+) 5 Nb8+! The knight insists on sacrificing himself to make his g-pawn hopefully promote. (5 g4 6. Nxf6 g3 7. Nh5 g2 8. Nf4!1) (5 Nb4+ 6. Kd6! (6. Kb5? Nd5 -+) 6 g4 7. Nxf6 g3 8. Nh5 =) 6. Nxb8 g4 At first glance, it might seem that this pawn is unstoppable now - but it will be stopped indeed! 7. Kd5 g3 8. Nc6 g2 9. Nd4 Threatens the same knight fork as in the 5g5-line. 9 Kd2 10. Ke4 f5+ 11. Kf4! (11. Kxf5? Ke3 -+) 11 Ke1 12. Nf3+ (12. Kxf5? Kf2 -+) 12 Kf2 After twelve moves from both sides, the re main ing stones suddenly and unexpectedly form the letter L. 13. Ng5! The final knight fork enables the draw. 1/2-1/2.

Isenegger =0070.11b2g6 (1951). Cooks, changed solution
